Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: AccessKenya Group, Sameer Kenya Move

-- B y   V i n c e n t   N w a n m a
-- 
2011-03-23T13:23:07Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-23/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-accesskenya-group-sameer-kenya-move.html
The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-
Share Index  climbed 0.8 percent to 25,195.05 at 1:40 p.m. in
Lagos, the highest intraday level in more than a week.  Mauritius’s SEMDEX Index increased for a third day, adding
0.4 percent to 1.978.94 at the 1:30 p.m. close in  Port Louis .
Kenya’s All-Share Index declined 0.5 percent to close at 72.13
at 3 p.m. in Nairobi, a fifth day of decreases. The Ghana Stock
Exchange Composite Index rose for a second day, adding 0.3
percent to 1,068.93 at 12:41 p.m. in Accra.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  AccessKenya (ACCESS)  Group Ltd. (ACCESS KN), the nation’s only
publicly traded Internet company, retreated for a third day,
losing 5 cents, or 0.6 percent, to 8.85 shillings. The company
reported a loss of 7.95 million shillings ($94,000) for the year
ended Dec. 31 compared wit a profit of 155.5 million shillings a
year earlier, the company said in a statement e-mailed to the
Nairobi bourse.  Sameer Africa Ltd. (SAME)  , a Kenyan tire manufacturer,
lost 5 cents, or 0.9 percent, to 5.7 shillings, a second day of
decreases. The company said profit in the year through December
more than halved to 57.4 million shillings from 158 million
shillings after raw-material and energy costs increased.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Vincent Nwanma in Lagos at 
 vnwanma@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
